The article discusses the continuation of the national emergency declared by President Barack Obama with respect to the situation in or in relation to Côte d'Ivoire. The national emergency was declared in 2006 and is in accordance with the International Emergency Economic Powers Act. The situation in Côte d'Ivoire has resulted in the massacre of civilians, human rights abuses, political violence, and attacks against international peacekeeping forces. While progress has been made in terms of democratic and economic development, the situation still poses a threat to the national security and foreign policy of the United States. Therefore, the national emergency will continue for another year. The United States is committed to helping Côte d'Ivoire strengthen its democracy and achieve lasting peace.